            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200517-106-person1086">
                  GEORGE 
                  STALLARD
               <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1086" type="surname" value="STALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1086" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1086" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am coachman to Lynch White, who is a <rs id="t18200517-106-viclabel623" type="occupation">livery-stable keeper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200517-106-victim1085 t18200517-106-viclabel623"></join>. On Friday, the 21st of April, I took a glass-coach to <placeName id="t18200517-106-crimeloc624">Covent-garden Theatre</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18200517-106-crimeloc624" type="placeName" value="Covent-garden Theatre"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18200517-106-crimeloc624" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200517-106-off621 t18200517-106-crimeloc624"></join>, between six and seven o'clock in the evening, the glass was safe then, on the Sunday following I missed it, I had not examined it before. I found it at St. Giles's watch-house, and compared it with the other - I am sure it is ours. I waited for the company at the Theatre, they came home at half-past ten o'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200517-106-person1087">
                  JOHN 
                  FURZEMAN
               <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1087" type="surname" value="FURZEMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1087" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200517-106-person1087" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On the 21st of April, about a quarter past ten o'clock at night, I saw the prisoner with two more men - I saw the prisoner shift the glass from one side of him to the other. I followed him into Covent-garden-market, and secured him; one of them said,</p>
               <p>"What does that bl - dy b - g - r want?" I took the glass, and secured the prisoner; he said he found it in Russell-street. I advertized it, and the prosecutor claimed it.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was coming from New-street, and picked it up against a post.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18200517-106-verdict625" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18200517-106-verdict625" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 25.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18200517-106-punish626" type="punishmentDescription">
